{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480204"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:39:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:39:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"25"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/25"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.57,0.04,0.04,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"25"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62978"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/25"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"25"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48429"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3026"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18504"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18516"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41959"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62978"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with her husband following ingestion of 24 paracetamol tablets. She lives on a remote cattle station in South Australia. She has a history of major depressive disorder and incomplete suicide by overdose two years ago. She takes sertraline and sees a psychologist monthly via telehealth. She works as a primary school teacher and has two children aged four and six years. Her husband reports she has been more withdrawn over the past month following a recent miscarriage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears withdrawn with minimal eye contact. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She acknowledges feeling hopeless but denies current suicidal thoughts. Mental state examination reveals no evidence of psychosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors would most significantly increase her risk of completed suicide?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recent disclosure of suicidal ideation to her psychologist","Access to firearms","Children starting school","Admitting her to hospital for involuntary treatment","Cross titrating to a tricyclic antidepressant due to treatment resistance"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a complex suicide risk assessment requiring consideration of multiple risk and protective factors. The patient has several established risk factors including previous suicide attempt, major depressive disorder, recent loss (miscarriage), and rural location. However, she also has protective factors including family support, employment, and regular mental health care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccess to firearms\u003C/strong\u003E is consistently shown to be the strongest predictor of completed suicide, particularly in rural and remote settings. The presence of firearms in the home increases suicide risk up to 5-fold, independent of other risk factors. This is due to the high lethality and immediacy of firearms compared to other methods.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecent disclosure of suicidal ideation to her psychologist\u003C/strong\u003E would actually be considered protective, as it demonstrates willingness to engage with mental health services and ability to communicate distress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChildren starting school\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely to significantly impact suicide risk. While major life transitions can be stressful, this is a normal developmental milestone and her children\u0027s school attendance may actually increase her social connections and daily structure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmitting her to hospital for involuntary treatment\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary for acute safety but has not been shown to reduce long-term suicide risk. In fact, the period following discharge from psychiatric admission carries elevated suicide risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECross titrating to a tricyclic antidepressant\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially increase risk due to the greater lethality of tricyclic antidepressants in overdose compared to selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors. However, this would be less significant than access to firearms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe assessment of suicide risk requires careful weighing of risk factors against protective factors. While individual protective factors may reduce risk, the presence of highly lethal means like firearms can override multiple protective factors, particularly in the context of impulsive acts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Access to firearms is the strongest predictor of completed suicide, particularly in rural settings","Protective factors like social support and responsibility for dependents must be weighed against risk factors in suicide assessment","The presence of multiple risk factors compounds overall suicide risk more than the sum of individual factors"],"references":["Campbell, W (2004).\u00a0Revised \u2018SAD PERSONS\u2019 helps assess suicide risk.\u00a0Accessed at:\u00a0https://www.mdedge.com/psychiatry/article/59790/depression/revised-sad-persons-helps-assess-suicide-risk.","RACGP \u2013 The Red Book (2020).\u00a010.2 Suicide.\u00a0Accessed at:\u00a0https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/red-book/psychosocial/suicide."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48429"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"25"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48429"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T13:50:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T13:57:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"25"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62978"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"